04235nam a22005415i 9780822394969DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223949697 a10.1515/97808223949692doi  a(DE-B1597)551940  a(OCoLC)1082920268  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3509.G4bF45 2012 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a781.65096672231 aFeld, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJazz Cosmopolitanism in Accra :bFive Musical Years in Ghana /cSteven Feld. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b78 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tSET LIST -- tOpus -- tFOUR-BAR INTRO ''The Shape of Jazz to Come'' -- tVAMP IN, HEAD Acoustemology in Accra: On Jazz Cosmopolitanism -- tFIRST CHORUS, WITH TRANSPOSITION Guy Warren/Ghanaba: From Afro-Jazz to Handel via Max Roach -- tSECOND CHORUS, BLOW FREE Nii Noi Nortey: From Pan-Africanism to Afrifones via John Coltrane -- tTHIRD CHORUS, BACK INSIDE Nii Otoo Annan: From Toads to Polyrhythm via Elvin Jones and Rashied Ali -- tFOURTH CHORUS, SHOUT TO THE GROOVE Por Por: From Honk Horns to Jazz Funerals via New Orleans -- tHEAD AGAIN, VAMP OUT Beyond Diasporic Intimacy -- t''DEDICATED TO YOU'' -- tHORN BACKGROUNDS, RIFFS UNDERNEATH -- tTHEMES, PLAYERS 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this remarkable book, Steven Feld, pioneer of the anthropology of sound, listens to the vernacular cosmopolitanism of jazz players in Ghana. Some have traveled widely, played with American jazz greats, and blended the innovations of John Coltrane with local instruments and worldviews. Combining memoir, biography, ethnography, and history, Feld conveys a diasporic intimacy and dialogue that contests American nationalist and Afrocentric narratives of jazz history. His stories of Accra's jazz cosmopolitanism feature Ghanaba/Guy Warren (1923-2008), the eccentric drummer who befriended the likes of Charlie Parker, Max Roach, and Thelonious Monk in the United States in the 1950s, only to return, embittered, to Ghana, where he became the country's leading experimentalist. Others whose stories figure prominently are Nii Noi Nortey, who fuses the legacies of the black avant-gardes of the 1960s and 1970s with pan-African philosophy in sculptural shrines to Coltrane and musical improvisations inspired by his work; the percussionist Nii Otoo Annan, a traditional master inspired by Coltrane's drummers Elvin Jones and Rashied Ali; and a union of Accra truck and minibus drivers whose squeeze-bulb honk-horn music for drivers' funerals recalls the jazz funerals of New Orleans. Feld describes these artists' cosmopolitan outlook as an "acoustemology," a way of knowing the world through sound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aJazz musicianszGhanazAccra. 0aJazzzGhanazAccray2001-2010xHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394969zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394969.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles